abstract: A roundup of things our editors — and a few contributors — are excited about in a given week.
snippet: A roundup of things our editors — and a few contributors — are excited about in a given week.
lead_paragraph: I’ve always felt that being in a room full of queer people as a queer person creates the uncanny sensation of experiencing the past and present at the same time: L.G.B.T.Q.+ people are never not aware of the activism and its art, the homophobia and its history, the disease and its death — all those bodies missing from the room — that have spurred them to live increasingly public lives, to gather and build an ever more powerful, visible, vibrant community. I thought about this again while viewing “Particular Voices: Photographs of LGBTQ Writers, Artists and Activists, 1980s – 1990s,” a show of 53 black-and-white portrait photographs taken by Robert Giard that are on display through July 26 at Daniel Cooney’s Chelsea gallery.

abstract: The debate between progressives and moderates never ends, but the party does best when neither side wins outright.

headline_main: Is There Anyone Who Can Unite the Democrats Besides Trump?

abstract: Kamala Harris gets a bump after the debates, Pete Buttigieg raises $24.8 million and Cory Booker unveils an immigration overhaul.
snippet: Kamala Harris gets a bump after the debates, Pete Buttigieg raises $24.8 million and Cory Booker unveils an immigration overhaul.
lead_paragraph: Every Saturday morning, we’re publishing “This Week in the 2020 Race”: a quick way to catch up on the presidential campaign and the field of 24 candidates for the Democratic nomination. Here’s our latest edition:

abstract: Fourteen candidates are assured a place onstage. The rest are battling it out for six remaining slots. In September, things get tougher.
snippet: Fourteen candidates are assured a place onstage. The rest are battling it out for six remaining slots. In September, things get tougher.
lead_paragraph: With just four weeks to go until the second set of Democratic presidential primary debates, a handful of lower-tier candidates are in danger of missing them. A single percentage point of support in one poll could be the difference between getting invited to Detroit and being left off the debate stage.

abstract: Let’s face it. It’s not a question you want to hear anyone asking about you.
snippet: Let’s face it. It’s not a question you want to hear anyone asking about you.
lead_paragraph: Gail Collins: Bret, the president’s been putting on quite a performance. Cavorting with Kim Jong-un in the DMZ and joking with Vladimir Putin about Russian interference in our presidential election, hehehe. Next, he’s planning to expropriate the traditional Independence Day celebration in Washington and turn it into some kind of Donald Does Democracy personal extravaganza.

abstract: But where do you draw the line? The Democratic candidates are contorting themselves trying to find the sweet spot.
snippet: But where do you draw the line? The Democratic candidates are contorting themselves trying to find the sweet spot.
lead_paragraph: How far to the left the Democrats are going has been a major topic of conversation in the first months of the contest for their party’s presidential nomination. One school of thought, which includes every Republican, holds that the Democrats have taken a sharp turn to the left and may be leaving some of the voters they need behind.
